<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Dragonsfyre</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Initiate<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jul 2000<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>I think pretty much everyone from the Shaman community up to Verant realises that Alchemy in it's current form is in dire need of a complete overhaul from the ground up.  I am posting this as my suggestions for a revamp of Alchemy.  I'm sure there are lots of ideas that can be added to it as well, just from reading the otrher posts in this forum.<br />
<br />
Skillcap<br />
--------<br />
First, Alchemy is the only Tradeskill that maxes out below 250, at 180.  There is no reason in my mind why this could not be remedied, and any overhaul of alchemy should start with this as it's first step.  Currently, Alchemy is limited by the level of the Shaman, starting with level 25.  While I do not believe that this restriction should be removed, I do think that the formula needs to be adjusted to accomodate the new Level 65 level limit, as well as allowing younger Shamans to start Alchemy at an earlier age.<br />
<br />
The current formula is as follows: (Level - 24) * 5 = Max Skill Allowed<br />
<br />
This provides for a max skill of 5 at level 25 up to a max skill of 180 at level 60.  If this formula was kept going forward into PoP, we could expect that the new max skill level would be 205, still nowhere near the 250 other tradeskills have.<br />
<br />
The formula I would propose is as follows: (Level - 14) * 5 = Max Skill Allowed<br />
<br />
This new formula would provide for a max skill of 5 starting at level 15, and go up to a max skill of 250 at level 65. This would provide us the ability to fully explore a wide variety of potential new potion possibilities.<br />
<br />
<br />
Prices<br />
------<br />
One of the longest running complaints from Shamans has been the prices for herbs and the buyback prices of potions.  Base herb prices has a tremendous impact on how saleable our potions are on the player market.  Buyback prices are mainly a matter of returning some portion of the amount spent on regents for potions that are not readily sellable on the open market.  Making a potion for 20pp that is not sellable to any player for that much money, yet returns only a little over 9gp from an NPC merchant, has been and is unacceptable.<br />
<br />
I don't think that anyone believes that Alchemy should make them rich.  Other than Jewelry making in the old days, or being at 250 skill with the recent PoTC quest, few tradeskillers in any skill make their fortune from their trade.  Also, just as most of the possible combinations in Jewelry and other skills have no viable PC market, not all potions should be viable to be sold to players.  The majority of them in fact would be in place primarily to build skill, not to make plat.  However, those potions for which there is absolutely no market must be sellable to a merchant for a minimum of 90% of the cost of the materials, just as manufactured Jewelry is for a jeweler.  Lost money would come from failed combines as it should be, not from successful ones.<br />
<br />
Obviously, setting prices for herbs is difficult due to the different economic conditions on the various servers.  On some servers, several potions may be more saleable than on others, based on their cost compared to the relative economic prosperity of the population.  Titan potions for example, which have little practical value, seem to sell much better for some Shamans than for others on other servers.  Whether this is purely an economic or a cultural difference is unknown, but it certainly must be accounted for.<br />
<br />
<br />
Recipe Complexity<br />
-----------------<br />
Virtually all of the tradeskills in the game have in the last year received an overhaul, making them far more viable to pursue beyond the 200 skill point.  In most cases, this has involved multi-step recipes, ingredients that are foraged or found as ground spawns or looted from mobs or purchased from other tradeskillers, the use of special tools or utensils, many of those having to be constructed in some fashion as well.  Some smithing recipes seem to be 10 steps deep.  In Alchemy, 90% of our potions are &quot;combine 2 or 3 store bought herbs in the medicine bag&quot; and there you go.  Old Alchemy had more of the &quot;find the ingredients&quot; type things, but most of those recipes are no more viable than the current Alchemy.<br />
<br />
Where are the multi-step potion recipes?  Where is our complexity?  To be honest, I'm not asking for Alchemy to become like Smithing.  I know few who could go thru that sadistic process to get to 250, and it would never be worth it.  However, there are tons of things that would make good Alchemy ingredients:<br />
<br />
- Items created by other tradeskills (brewing, baking, etc.)<br />
- Enchanted items from Enchanters (vials of mana, etc.)<br />
- Various summoned items (from Mages, Necros, etc.)<br />
- Foraged items (Herbs, Zone Essences, etc.)<br />
- Herbs that need to be Imbued or Enchanted in order to form the potion - Add a spell for doing this to our book<br />
- Ground spawns <br />
- Looted items<br />
<br />
<br />
Foraging<br />
--------<br />
It always amazes me that Shamans do not have the ability to forage for things in general, but specifically for Alchemy ingredients.  It totally fits with the mythos of the Shaman that they go out to the woods to find their herbs.  I can't imagine that giving Shamans the Foraging skill starting at Level 30 or 35 would unbalance anything in the game.  Considering how underappreciated the Shaman community feels today, this is a bone that VI could throw us that would cost them nothing.  If need be, it could be capped at 100 skill up to level 50, then 150 beyond there, although I don't see why it would need to be.  Foraged herbs could be a great thing for alchemy and doesn't negatively impact anyone.<br />
<br />
<br />
Stat Potions<br />
------------<br />
Basically, stat potions are never going to be something that the Shaman can readily sell, no matter what the price, unless they were made so good or so cheap as to be unbalancing to the game.  In my opinion, these potions exist only to raise skill.  As stated above, buyback prices must be increased to make these more than just a moneysink for the fledgling alchemist.  The same is true of resist stat potions.<br />
<br />
<br />
Utility Potions<br />
---------------<br />
Here is the bread and butter of Alchemy.  Shrink, Invis to Undead, Levitate, Enduring Breath, SoW, Regen, Damage Shield, etc.  This is what the players are interested in, what they will buy if the price is right, and the area that expansion is needed in the most.  We have Invis to Undead potions but not Invis potions.  We should be capable of making Invis potions that are 10 charge, as carrying around a bunch of invis potions is a pain.<br />
<br />
<br />
Mind Buff Potions<br />
-----------------<br />
The existing collection of mind-buff potions are not only a joke but a bad joke at that.  I can't imagine anyone being willing to pay so much for so little return.  They may as well not even be in the game.  The thing that bugs me is that there are SO MANY viable mana-related potions that could be created that would be useful, saleable additions to our repetoire.  The key is in the economics.  Today, and for some time to come, almost anyone over level 20 is willing to pay their local enchanter 100pp for a shot of KEI.  The niche potions need to fill is for when there is no 60 Enchanter around, and you don't want to run back to Nexus for a KEI recharge.  These potions would be far more affordable and powerful than those already in the game, but by keeping them in their proper niche, basically meainging not quite as good as a real mind buff, but less expensive, we keep things in balance.  Here are some mana-based potions I would create if I could:<br />
<br />
Lesser Concentration - Trivial 80 - Breeze + 50 Mana - 15 Min Duration - Cost 10pp - Herb Ingredients<br />
Concentration - Trivial 130 - Clarity + 100 Mana - 25 Min Duration - Cost 20pp - Herbs, Vial of Viscious Mana<br />
Greater Concentration - Triv 180 - Clarity 2 + 150 Mana (L45 Limit) - 35 Min Dur - 40pp	- Herbs, Vial of Cloudy Mana<br />
Endless Concentration - Triv 230 - KEI - 90 Min Duration (L50 Limit) - 80pp - Herbs, Vial of Clear Mana<br />
Lesser Mana Restoration - Triv 90 - Gives 100 Mana for 80 Health /tick over 5 ticks	25pp - Herb Ingredients<br />
Mana Restoration - Triv 140 - Restores 200 Mana for 160 Health /tick over 5 ticks - 	50pp - Herbs, Vial of Viscious Mana<br />
Greater Mana Rest. - Triv 190 - 400 Mana for 200 Health /tick over 5 ticks - 100pp - Herbs, Vial of Cloudy Mana, Mod Rod<br />
Endless Mana Rest. - Triv 240 - 1000 Mana for 300 Health /tick over 5 ticks - 150pp - Herbs, Vial of Clear Mana, Mod Rod 3<br />
<br />
Gate Potions<br />
------------<br />
Everyone pretty much agrees that Gate potions take too long to cast, have very limited locations available and cost too much.  The OT gate Hammer and Thurgadin pottery potion have also lowered the demand for our potions significantly.  It is my feeling that in addition to adding a Potion of the Moor for the Vah Shir Shamans, going to Hollowshade Moor, that there should be 2 potions to each of the locations, one of which costs the current 168pp each but has a 5 or even 3 second casting time, and the second potion being the same 30 second casting time as the current potions, with a much lower price.<br />
<br />
New Potions<br />
-----------<br />
Listed below are some possible postions that could be added to fill in the skill range to 250.  The first section is Illusion Potions.  I don't know why Verant would not allow something like this, in that it is a limited use kind of thing.  It would mainly be used as a toy but could in some circumstances allow characters to do quests, etc., that they otherwise might have a hard time completing for racial reasons.<br />
<br />
Illusion: Barbarian - Triv 220 - Illusion: Barbarian, +20 Cold - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana, Frost Essence<br />
Illusion: Dark Elf - Triv 235 - Illusion: Dark Elf, +20 Dis - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana, Nektulos Essence<br />
Illusion: Dwarf - Triv 245 - Illusion: Dwarf, +20 STR - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana, Butcherblock Essence<br />
Illusion: Erudite - Triv 250 -  Illusion: Erudite, +20 INT - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana, Erud's Essence<br />
Illusion: Gnome - Triv 240 - Illusion:  Gnome, +20 Fire - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana, Clockwork Essence<br />
Illusion: Half Elf - Triv 250 - Illusion: Half Elf, +20 Poi - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana, Thunder Essence<br />
Illusion: Halfling - Triv 240 - Illusion: Halfling, +20 DEX - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana, Vale Essence<br />
Illusion: High Elf - Triv 235 - Illusion: High Elf, +20 CHA - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana, Faydark Essence<br />
Illusion: Human - Triv 220 - Illusion: Human, +20 Mag - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana, Marr Essence<br />
Illusion: Iksar - Triv 230 - Illusion: Iksar, +20 AC - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana, Cabilis Essence<br />
Illusion: Ogre - Triv 225 - Illusion: Ogre, +20 STA - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana, Feerott Essence<br />
Illusion: Troll - Triv 225 - Illusion: Troll, +2 HP Regen per tick - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana, Innothule Essence<br />
Illusion: Vah Shir - Triv 230 - Illusion: Vah Shir, +20 AGI - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana, Shar Val Essence<br />
Illusion: Wood Elf - Triv 245 - Illusion: Wood Elf, +20 WIS - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana,  Vital Essence<br />
Illusion: Skeleton - Triv 215 - Illusion: Skeleton, Effect: Lich - Cost 110pp - Herbs, Cloudy Mana, Essence Emerald<br />
Illusion: Spectre - Triv &gt;250 - Illusion: Spectre, Effect: Arch Lich - Cost 220pp - Herbs, Clear Mana, Essence Emerald<br />
<br />
Cursed Reviviscence - Triv &gt;250 - Effect: Reviviscence, Res Effects last 1 game day - Cost 250pp - Herbs, Clear Mana, Essence Emerald, Celestial Essence<br />
<br />
Other Ressurection type spells may be possible, although they show the most potential for being unbalancing.<br />
<br />
Upgrades to the Rejuvenation, Damage Shield, and other potions would be nice.  An enhanced EB potion that does not require a fishscale, or lev that does not require a batwing, would be great.  Perhaps make part of the recipe a mage summoned lev ring for the no regent lev potion, and similar for the EB potion, effectively turning the No Rent Mage summoned items into non-No Rent potions using Alchemy.<br />
<br />
<br />
There are lots more ideas out there....now if only VI will listen and act.<br />
<br />
